{"id":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.060504","title":{"value":"Electrohydrodynamic instabilities of viscous drops","format":"html+mathml"},"publisher":{"name":"APS"},"journal":{"id":"PRFLUIDS","abbreviatedName":"Phys. Rev. Fluids","name":"Physical Review Fluids"},"issue":{"number":"6"},"volume":{"number":"1"},"pageStart":"060504","hasArticleId":true,"date":"2016-10-18","numPages":9,"articleType":"article","identifiers":{"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.060504"},"rights":{"rightsStatement":"Â©2016 American Physical Society","copyrightYear":2016,"copyrightHolders":[{"name":"American Physical Society"}]},"authors":[{"type":"Person","name":"Petia M. Vlahovska","firstname":"Petia M.","surname":"Vlahovska","affiliationIds":["a1"]}],"affiliations":[{"id":"a1","name":"School of Engineering, Brown University, Providence, Rhode Island 02912, USA"}],"abstract":{"value":"<p>A classic result due to Taylor is that a weakly conducting drop bearing zero net charge placed in a uniform electric field adopts a prolate or oblate spheroidal shape, the flow and shape being axisymmetrically aligned with the applied field. Here I overview some intriguing symmetry-breaking instabilities occurring in strong applied dc fields: Quincke rotation resulting in drop steady tilt or tumbling, and pattern formation on the surface of a particle-coated drop.</p>","format":"html+mathml"},"classificationSchemes":{"physh":{"disciplines":[{"id":"6f025065-4b96-4156-b146-2c285d0994c4","label":"Nonlinear Dynamics"},{"id":"512fd433-7b6d-4535-bb60-78f3bf431bc3","label":"Fluid Dynamics"}],"concepts":[{"id":"578d4bf5-0835-4227-813c-1e32ad36601f","label":"Induced-charge flows","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"},"primary":true},{"id":"f5372742-fa5e-4bda-96ba-87e45d98bae6","label":"Interfacial flows","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"af1f8b12-9181-4c18-a750-d9e9fe621217","label":"Bifurcations","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8